ETSP Microbiome and Plasmodium

Import 16S Data

Start by importing Mothur-generated dataset and metadata from 2020 using the package phyloseq. Combine the files into a single phyloseq object.

library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(phyloseq)
library(readxl)

##Import data from 2020 and make into phyloseq object
mothur_20 <- import_mothur(mothur_shared_file = "~/Research/Plas_microbiome_submission/R_files/ETSP_batch1_2020.shared", 
                           mothur_constaxonomy_file = "~/Research/Plas_microbiome_submission/R_files/ETSP_batch1_2020.taxonomy")
metadata_20 <- read_excel(path="~/Research/Plas_microbiome_submission/R_files/metadata_2020.xlsx")
map_20 <- sample_data(metadata_20) # convert metadata into phyloseq sample_data
rownames(map_20) <-map_20$id  #fix problem recognizing sample names
etsp_20 <- merge_phyloseq(map_20, mothur_20)
sample_names(etsp_20)

Now import the 16S dataset from 2021 using the same steps.

##Import data from 2021 and make into phyloseq object
mothur_21 <- import_mothur(mothur_shared_file = "~/Research/Plas_microbiome_submission/R_files/ETSP_batch2_2021.shared", mothur_constaxonomy_file = "~/Research/Plas_microbiome_submission/R_files/ETSP_batch2_2021.taxonomy")

Merge both datasets from 2020 and 2021 into a single phyloseq object. Label rank names.

all_data <- merge_phyloseq(etsp_20, etsp_21)

rank_names(all_data)
colnames(tax_table(all_data)) <- c("Kingdom", "Phylum", "Class", "Order", "Family", "Genus" )
rank_names(all_data)

sample_names(all_data)

Use the package decontam to detect potential contaminants from the negative controls and to remove them from the dataset. Then remove all non-sparrow samples (e.g. controls) from the dataset.

library(decontam)

dec <- subset_samples(all_data, decontam!="NA")

#Prevalence method - decontam
sample_data(dec)$is.neg <- sample_data(dec)$decontam == "negative"
contamdf.prev <- isContaminant(dec, method="prevalence", neg="is.neg")
table(contamdf.prev$contaminant)
##FALSE   TRUE 
##11334     2 
head(which(contamdf.prev$contaminant))
##[1]   59 7350

# Make phyloseq object of presence-absence in negative controls and samples
ps.pa <- transform_sample_counts(dec, function(abund) 1*(abund>0))
ps.pa.neg <- prune_samples(sample_data(ps.pa)$decontam == "negative", ps.pa)
ps.pa.pos <- prune_samples(sample_data(ps.pa)$decontam == "sample", ps.pa)
# Make data.frame of prevalence in positive and negative samples
df.pa <- data.frame(pa.pos=taxa_sums(ps.pa.pos), pa.neg=taxa_sums(ps.pa.neg),
                    contaminant=contamdf.prev$contaminant)
ggplot(data=df.pa, aes(x=pa.neg, y=pa.pos, color=contaminant)) + geom_point() +
  xlab("Prevalence (Negative Controls)") + ylab("Prevalence (Samples)")

##Remove contaminants from samples
dec
clean_ps <- prune_taxa(!contamdf.prev$contaminant, dec)
clean_ps

#Remove negative controls, leaving cleaned sparrow samples from Columbia Bottom CA and Webster Groves. 
clean_ps <- subset_samples(clean_ps, decontam=="sample")
clean_ps

Remove unclassified bacteria, check sample read depth, and subsample to 4422 reads. This excludes 6 samples.

##Alpha Diversity Calculate Alpha Diversity with phyloseq, using four common diversity measurements. Convert alpha diversity into phyloseq sample_data. Merge the alpha diversity object with the primary phyloseq object so the alpha diversity values are included in the overall sample data.

ad <- estimate_richness(twosites, measures=c("Observed", "Shannon", "Simpson", "InvSimpson"))
ad <- sample_data(ad)
twosites <- merge_phyloseq(twosites, ad)
twosites

Pull sample data and test normality visually and statistically.

library(ggpubr)
alpha <- sample_data(twosites)

ggqqplot(alpha$Observed)
ggdensity(alpha$Observed)
ggqqplot(alpha$Shannon)
ggdensity(alpha$Shannon)
ggqqplot(alpha$Simpson)
ggdensity(alpha$Simpson)
ggqqplot(alpha$InvSimpson)
ggdensity(alpha$InvSimpson)

shapiro.test(alpha$Observed)
## Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## data:  alpha$Observed
## W = 0.95659, p-value = 0.006874

shapiro.test(alpha$Shannon)
## Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## data:  alpha$Shannon
## W = 0.98197, p-value = 0.2967

shapiro.test(alpha$Simpson)
## Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## data:  alpha$Simpson
## W = 0.85161, p-value = 1.219e-07

shapiro.test(alpha$InvSimpson)
## Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## data:  alpha$InvSimpson
## W = 0.5547, p-value = 1.793e-14

Shannon Diversity appears normally distributed, and observed richness looks okay visually but is significant with Shapiro Wilks. Simpson and InvSimpson are not normally distributed. Plot Plasmodium alpha diversity to visualize possible variation.

ggplot(alpha, aes(x = plasmodium, y = Observed)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(alpha, aes(x = plasmodium, y = Shannon)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

No apparent visual difference. Use ANOVAs to check statistically - test observed richness and Shannon Diversity while accounting for confounding variables.

alpha_df <- as(sample_data(twosites), "data.frame")
alpha_df

anova <- aov(Observed ~ batch + age + location + plasmodium, data = alpha_df)
summary(anova)

Check significance of Plasmodium using PERMANOVAs across both sites.

library(vegan)

wgcb_jac <- phyloseq::distance(twosites, method = "jaccard")
wgcb_df <- data.frame(sample_data(twosites))

perm <- how(nperm = 999)
setBlocks(perm) <- with(wgcb_df, batch)

adonis2(wgcb_jac ~ location + season + sex + age + plasmodium, data = wgcb_df, permutations=perm)

Load the package DESeq2 and convert the phyloseq object to DESeq2. Put covariates into the formula with the variable of interest placed at the end (far right). Use relevel() to make sure that the reference level is set to “N” for uninfected individuals. After running the model, doublecheck the output by using mcols(res)$description.

library(DESeq2)
dstwo <- phyloseq_to_deseq2(filtered, ~ batch + age + season + location + plasmodium)

gm_mean = function(x, na.rm=TRUE){
  exp(sum(log(x[x > 0]), na.rm=na.rm) / length(x))
}
geoMeans = apply(counts(dstwo), 1, gm_mean)

dstwo = estimateSizeFactors(dstwo, geoMeans = geoMeans)

#Use relevel to make sure that uninfected individuals are set as the reference level 
dstwo$plasmodium = relevel(dstwo$plasmodium, "N")
dstwo$plasmodium

#Run DESeq2
dstwo = DESeq(dstwo)

res = results(dstwo)
res = res[order(res$padj, na.last=NA), ]
alpha = 0.01  ##Default is 0.1
sigtab = res[(res$padj < alpha), ]
sigtab = cbind(as(sigtab, "data.frame"), as(tax_table(filtered)[rownames(sigtab), ], "matrix"))
head(sigtab)

plotMA(res)

#Check what the model tested
mcols(res)$description
##[1] "mean of normalized counts for all samples" "log2 fold change (MLE): plasmodium Y vs N"
##[3] "standard error: plasmodium Y vs N"         "Wald statistic: plasmodium Y vs N"        
##[5] "Wald test p-value: plasmodium Y vs N"      "BH adjusted p-values"

Plot with Families and Phyla. Most of the significant taxa are enriched for infected individuals. Graph shows infected individuals relative to undetected.

library("ggplot2")

sigtabfam <- subset(sigtab, !is.na(Family))
# Phylum order
x = tapply(sigtabfam$log2FoldChange, sigtabfam$Phylum, function(x) max(x))
x = sort(x, TRUE)
sigtabfam$Phylum = factor(as.character(sigtabfam$Phylum), levels=names(x))
# Family order
x = tapply(sigtabfam$log2FoldChange, sigtabfam$Family, function(x) max(x))
x = sort(x, TRUE)
sigtabfam$Family = factor(as.character(sigtabfam$Family), levels=names(x))
des_phyla <- ggplot(sigtabfam, aes(y=Family, x=log2FoldChange, color=Phylum)) + 
  xlab(expression(~Log[2]~Fold~Change)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.0, color = "gray", size = 1) +
  geom_point(size=3) + 
  scale_fill_brewer(labels = c(expression(italic("Firmicutes", "Proteobacteria", "Planctomycetes", "Actinobacteria")))) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = -90, hjust = 0, vjust=0.5)) +
  theme_bw()
des_phyla <- des_phyla + theme(text = element_text(family = "serif"))
des_phyla
